postcontent:
We have a new Century International Arms GP-WASR 10/63 Semi Auto AK47 style rifle for sale. This is chambered in 7.62x39. It comes in box with 2-30 round magazines, bayonett and owners manual. 

MFG Description:
The Century International Arms GP WASR-10 is a semi-automatic only rendition of the famous 7.62x39 mm AKM rifle configured with a fixed laminated stock and a laminated forend. Manufactured in Romania, the 7.62x39 mm GP WASR-10 is imported as a single stack rifle that accepts single column 10-round magazines. title: For Sale/Trade:  Thompson 1911A1 U.S. Army LNIB w/Extras
postcontent:
I have for sale or trade a LNIB Auto Ordnance Thompson 1911A1 WWII Parkerized .45ACP in the box with all papers, cable lock, and four magazines full of 45ACP FMJ ammo. It has a set of Pierce Rubber combat grips installed, and the original checkered wood grips are with it, too. This is a MADE IN AMERICA 1911, not from the Philipines or Turkey as so many new 1911's are now. I am asking $650 cash or will consider trades. Following is an article about the gun I found online for your consideration: 

Auto-Ordnance Thompson 1911-A1 World War II Parkerized, .45 ACP 5" Barrel, Parkerized Finish, 7 Round Magazine

After almost 20 years, still remain hand assembled, American made and produced with finest 4140 steel. For a multitude of purposes; home defense, competition or recreational shooting. WWII Parkerized Basic military version. Features original G.I. detailing throughout right down to the military style rollstamp, plasticgrips and lanyard loop.

Out of the box, the Auto-Ordnance 1911 looks to be a newly manufactured twin to a World War II 1911A1 with some exceptions. The finish is similar to that used by the 1911 manufacturers during WWII, which was either a Parco-Lubrite finish, a manganese-based phosphating process used by Colt, or Parkerizing, which uses a zinc base. The Parker Rustproof Company of Detroit, Michigan developed both processes. The more familiar green-and-gray-hued finish fond on many U.S.WWII military arms came later.

The grip panels are checked brown plastic and the arched mainspring housing has the obligatory lanyard loop. The sights are identical to the WWII guns, with small ramped front and square notch rear. The Auto-Ordnance uses a seven-round Metalform magazine with the normal flat-shelf follower but with an easily removable metal base plate. (The Metal Form Corporation made magazines during WWII, but I''m not sure if the current company and the historical company share a lineage.)

The slide serrations are slanted as is found on Drake-manufactured National Match slides and also the Colt Gold Cup model, rather than running vertically, as on the original. The ejection port window is lower (that is, larger) than on the WWII guns. The Auto-Ordnance 1911 uses a long, grooved 1911 trigger rather than the short, stamped 1911A1 trigger, and the frame is scalloped behind the triggerguard as is normal for 1911A1 pistols.

title: For Sale:  Springfield Armory 1911 Loaded W/ Holster
postcontent:
I bought this thing a few weeks ago from my FFL. It belonged to a guy who was an officer in the Marines and kept it as a home defense weapon. The gun was made in 1998/1999 according to SA via a serial number look up. The previous owner hardly put any rounds through it according to my FFL and the gun looked to reflect that. There are some scratches and marring that occurred from use. I took it to the range after completely stripping and cleaning it and put 200 rounds through it no problems at all. The recoil in these things is pretty light for a .45 most likely due to its weight.

It is a very solid, well made gun as most 1911's are. Included is the original box (one of the hinges is broken), manuals, 2 magazines, stock wood grips, and a new pair of SA wooden grips that were take offs from a new 1911.

The gun worked perfectly, zero problems, and is a good reputation of the 1911. Unfortunately despite its appeal with gun owners I was not too impressed. Shooting it after shooting my S+W M&P was like night and day in terms of ergonomics which I suppose is not a surprise considering the 100 years between the designs.

If you are interested feel free to call or text me at REDACTED. If I do not answer please leave a voice mail. You can also e-mail me.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Finnish M39 Mosin Nagant Sale Pending
postcontent: Up for trade or sale is a 1942 B barreled Finnish M39 Mosin Nagant. This is a harder to find variation of the M39, which is one of the most accurate of the milsurp rifles. It is chambered in the ever plentiful and affordable 7.62x54r cartridge and it is a tack driver. I don't believe that this rifle was ever issued, as it is claimed the B barrels were made in Nazi Occupied Belgium at the FN plant and never made it to Finland before the war ended. This rifle is in great shape, the stock is beautiful with a few handling marks. The barrel is in excellent condition and most of the bluing remains. Numbers match and this Finn was built on a 1913 Izhevsk receiver, so it turns 100 years next year! $400 obo have some ammo and chargers to throw in as well. Prefer local deals, will drive within reason or ship for the right deal.

title: For Sale:  PROFESSIONAL BANK LOCK BOX - W / 6 COMPARTMENTS
postcontent:
For sale; one (1) used, unitized 6-compartment bank-grade unit. This one is the type normally found in credit unions and banks and variously called "teller boxes" and "cash tray drawers" due to their larger size compartments. 

Unit is rectangular in shape, there are six (6) doors - three (3) to each side of the center and placed top-to-bottom. All doors are keyed separately. This is not a thick-walled, heavy safe. It can be used as a lockable storage for valuables; just set it up on a stout end table or closer to floor and "conceal" it. It is heavy, but still very transportable until you add your stuff (weight). Could also be used for a built-in application - like banks do. 

Approx. exterior size is 32 1/2" long X 16" high X 24" long. Again, there are six (6) lockable compartments of 15 3/4" X 5" X 24" EACH so these have a lot of room. All have their own lockable door and safe-deposit style keys. Also, each drawer has it's own set of keys. They are keyed separately. 

This is a used, commercial-grade unit and perfect for handguns, ammo and other valuables.

title: For Sale:  Ruger 10/22 Takedown Shooting Team
postcontent:
The USA Shooting Team Ruger 10/22 Takedown is a stainless steel rifle with a distinct blue stock. Like all 10/22 Takedown™ rifles, the barrel and forend are easily separated from the action and buttstock by pushing a recessed lever, twisting the subassemblies, and pulling them apart. Reassembly is the reverse of takedown, and is quick and easy.

The friction-fit lockup of the assembly joint is simple to adjust, but rarely needs re-adjustment after the first assembly. The lockup is secure and repeatable, ensuring an accurate return to zero, even when receiver-mounted optics are used.

The USA Shooting Team Ruger 10/22 Takedown™ is also shipped in a special red ballistic nylon backpack-style case that features the USA Shooting Team logo. The bag features internal sleeves, which hold the two subassemblies.

External pockets with MOLLE webbing provide storage for magazines, ammunition and other accessories. Multiple attachment points for the padded, single shoulder strap offer different carrying options.


Read more at Ammoland.com: http://www.ammoland.com/2012/07/26/usa-shooting-team-ruger-1022-takedown/#ixzz2D61QIbop
